Imo State Governor, Rt. Hon. Emeka Ihedioha has assured the Federal Government of his administration’s commitment to collaborate with it to find lasting solution to the lingering land dispute between the Federal University of Technology, Owerri (FUTO) and its host communities.  Ihedioha spoke when he received in audience, the Minister of State for Education, Hon. Emeka Nwajiuba, alongside a delegation from the Federal University of Technology. The governor stated that his commitment to resolving the land dispute was in line with the priority of his administration had placed on education and amicable conflict resolution in the state, noting that Imo State was known for its high literacy level in the country.  He, however, commended President Muhammadu Buhari for appointing Hon. Nwajiuba as a Minis ter of the Federal Republic of Nigeria. Ihedioha said: “We have a common goal in the area of education because education is very important to us in Imo State. We will dialogue with you to achieve the desired results. “On behalf of the people of Imo State, we extend our gratitude to Mr. President for appointing Hon. Nwajiuba as a Minister.   “Your trajectory from the House of Representatives to your appointment as a Minister is well appreciated by the people of the State. You are a son in whom we are well pleased.” In his opening remarks, the Minister of State for Education, Hon. Emeka Nwajiuba, said the Federal Ministry of Education decided to review its position on the FUTO land issue because of the renewed spirit and commitment demonstrated by the state government to end the lingering dispute.